         <abstract>
            <p>Capital market theory implies that for any given level of risk, the greatest expected reward will be associated with a truly balanced portfolio--one in which investments are represented in proportion to their market values. From 1938 to 1971 this strategy demonstrated a reward to variability ratio superior to any strategy employing a constant proportion of bonds and stocks, including of course the strategies of holding all bonds or all stocks. The appropriate question is not "Why bonds?" or "Why stocks?", but rather "Why not bonds and stocks in proportion to market values?".</p>
          </abstract>
